<subsection xml:id="subsec_Using_R_Instat_Specifying_hypothesis">
  <title>Using R-Instat: Specifying hypotheses</title>
  <p>
      In R-Instat, the null and alternative hypotheses are specified through dialog boxes rather than written symbolically.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, when using the One Variable Fit Model:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The null hypothesis is entered directly in the "Null Hypothesis" field.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The alternative hypothesis is determined by the type of test selected (e.g., two-sided or one-sided).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    The software then automatically constructs the appropriate statistical test based on these inputs.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig-specifyhypotheses">
    <caption> The One Variable Fit Model dialog in R-Instat. </caption>
    <image source="images/HypothesisTesting/Model one variable General Case dialogue work pay data Normal.png"/>
  </figure>


  <figure xml:id="OneVariableTestOptions">
    <caption>The user specifies the variable, selects the test type</caption>
    <image source="images/HypothesisTesting/Model one variable Test dialogue work pay data T test.png"/>
  </figure>



  <figure xml:id="OneVariableDialoguetTest">
    <caption>The user enters the null hypothesis value. The confidence level determines the significance level of the test.</caption>
      <image source="images/HypothesisTesting/Model one variable Test dialogue work pay data T test 30 null hypothesis.png"/>
  </figure>
</subsection>
